openly gay service members in the U.S. military was lifted. An increasing number of states and towns have passed laws against anti-gay discrimination. In 2013 a major supreme court case, the United States v. Windsor, resulted in the Supreme Court striking down part of a law that banned federal recognition of same-sex marriages. Soon after, another Supreme Court ruling (Obergefell v. Hodges) made same-sex marriage legal throughout the nation. These rulings mean that married same-sex couples are now entitled to the same rights enjoyed by heterosexual married couples. These rights include Social Security benefits, hospital visitation rights, healthcare benefits, and military family benefits. However, despite these advances, LGBT people still have no federal law to protect them from discrimination in housing or employment.

An Aging Population

While the life expectancy of an American born in 1900 was less than 50 years, an American born in 2011 can expect to live to about 79. By 2000, older Americans tended to retire earlier, live longer, and exert more political influence. These factors have strained the country’s social welfare system, especially Social Security and Medicare. In 2010, the federal government spent less than 300 billion on social welfare. By 2013, the amount had increased to $1.9 trillion.

With the large baby-boom generation reaching retirement age, the issues of elder care has become critical. Falling birthrates over the past two decades have meant that when the huge population of baby boomers retires, there will not be enough workers to cover their Social Security benefits. Politicians have been debating this impending crisis.

In his second term, President Obama called for privatizing Social Security by allowing younger workers to invest some of their earnings in individual retirement accounts outside of the system. In this way, he said it would give younger workers the security of fluctuating stock markets and the appalling address the abolition of trust funds. Today the debate continues.

Energy and the Environment

On June 25, 2013, President Obama addressed an audience at Georgetown University on the subject of the environment. Briefly mentioning how bad the current waves in recorded history had come over the course of the previous fifteen years, he focused on the problem of global warming:

Last year, temperatures in some areas of the ocean reached record highs, and ice in the Arctic shrank to its smallest size on record—faster than most models had predicted it would. These are facts.

—President Obama, Georgetown University, June 25, 2013

Coastal areas of the United States will be under threat if, as many scientists predict, the warming of the atmosphere leads to a rise in sea levels. In low-lying areas of Florida, high tides are already leading to events floods, especially in cities such as Miami. With Florida heavily dependent on tourism, an increase in sea levels could seriously affect the state’s economy. In Hawaii, there is concern that sea levels, which have been rising for the last 100 years, may accelerate, threatening urban areas.

Global warming has implications far beyond rising seas. The Environmental Protection Agency notes that in Alaska, where the increase in average temperatures is more than twice the warming in the rest of the United States, forest fires are increasing, while sea ice is decreasing. Warming is also changing winter, and permafrost is thawing. This melting permafrost, which may lead to ground subsidence, is a direct threat to transportation networks and buildings.

Legislating to Protect the Environment

In recent years, environmental issues have aroused political controversy. Some deny that our planet is experiencing the kind of warming temperatures that most scientists believe we are experiencing. Others admit that such warming is the product of human activity, especially the burning of fossil fuels. Almost all agree that if global warming were taking place, the government would have to pass legislation requiring Americans to change many of their comfortable habits.

Nonetheless, since the 1970s the United States has passed a variety of laws designed to protect the environment. Global warming has made these issues more urgent. During the 1990s the government was reluctant to pass regulations that might harm American businesses. In this argument about environmental legislation is partly an extension of the nation’s individualism.

During the Obama administration, regulations began to restrict carbon emissions from power plants, prompting many coal industry officials to condemn the regulations as a “war on coal.” To combat climate change, the government set a goal of reducing carbon emissions while increasing the use of renewable energy. When Donald Trump became president, he announced his intention of removing or rolling back many of Obama’s climate policies. His administration reduced and eliminated steps the government claimed would improve clean air and the health of people and protect Americans from climate change.

The Environment and Local Economies

Recently, environmental issues have become closely tied to local business concerns. For instance, in the Southwest, home to four main environmental regions—the desert, the coastal, the forest, and the Midwest. In the West, water is an important environmental and economic issue because it is so scarce. Population growth and drought put pressure on this precious resource, which must be shared by private homes and businesses. Recent periods of drought in California, which persist in parts of the state, have had a dramatic effect on the state’s farming economy.

The West is also a region with vast tracts of land owned by the federal government. The government’s management of this land touches issues of mining, logging, grazing, and tourism and development. Recently, one proposed area of gas and development on public land has become a controversial issue.

Other regions face different environmental issues. The 2010 Deepwater Horizon oil spill in the Gulf of Mexico created environmental problems all along the Gulf Coast. Another controversial issue is the Keystone XL pipeline project that transfers crude oil from Canada to the Midwest, routes legislation to stop it. This pipeline, which would pass in the Gulf of Mexico, was opposed by President Obama but approved by President Trump. Critics opposed this energy project for its possible damage to the environment, while the project’s supporters complain that it will bring jobs and help enhance oil supply.

President Obama’s Climate Action Plan

EPA REGULATORY GOALS

  • Speed up the process of implementing regulations to reduce greenhouse gas emissions
  • Issue flexible regulations to individual states to help reduce emissions
  • Replace use of hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs) in the United States with alternatives
  • Promote scientific research and development
  • Work with foreign, state, and local governments to solve issues
  • Improve the EPA’s internal management and workforce
  • Empower communities to advance the cause of environmental protection
  • Support the Presidential Council for an Advanced Energy Economy

SOURCE: Presidential Climate Action Project
